term_definitions.items: Zip code of the subject's address (it might only be a part of it)
Used for admitted patient only. It signals the beginning of a patient's stay in a health care facility.
The circumstance under which the patient will be admitted.
Clinician who referred patient to the consulting doctor
For local use, this field hold the type of organizational unit or clinical unit, e.g. CARDO1.
Refer to NHDD 000385 Mode of admission and NHDD 000150 Source of referral to public psychiatric hospital
Assigned patient location when the patient was admitted.
The attending doctor providing services to the patient
Consultant responsible for the care of the patient,including salaried specialist, visiting medical officer
Motor vehicle third party personal claim
Other compensation (e.g. public liability, common law, medical negligence)
Other hospital or public authority (contracted care)
Reciprocal health care agreements (with other countries)
Specialty assigned to this health event (it can be different from that in the patient's location)
The regimen admission is made: hospital, day-hospital,...
Link to Clinical event summary document

An issue or obstacle which adversely impacts on the physical, mental and/or social well-being of an individual. The definition of a problem is deliberately kept rather loose and inclusive of a formal biomedical diagnosis so as to capture any real or perceived concerns that may adversely affect an individual's wellbeing to any degree.
Identification of the index problem, issue or diagnosis.
The date / time when the problem was first identified by the individual.
The age of the individual when the problem was first identified by the individual.
Coding of the severity with a terminology is preferred, where possible.
The assessed overall severity of the index problem.
A narrative description of the issue, problem or diagnosis.
Grouping of information about individual occurrences or exacerbations.
The frequency of individual occurrences of the problem.
The date / time of the last occurrence of the problem.
A description of the exacerbation or occurrence.
Number of times this problem has occurred or been apparent.
A group of characteristics of the problem complicating the index problem.
Identification of a related problem as text,coded text or link within the EHR.
The type of relationship that this problem/diagnosis has to the related item.
The date that the problem resolved or went into remission.
The age of the person at the resolution of the problem.
Useful information on the internet about this condition.
Details of the body site concerned.

This concept identifies the direct cause or causative agent of a Problem/Diagnosis. The concept includes the idea of ‘complications’, ‘causative agent’ and ‘due to’. Note: Where no causality or sequence of events is known, this relationship type should be left blank.

This value identifies the sequence of events between the related items, but does not assert causality. This can be used for sequelae or late effects. Note: Where no causality or sequence of events is known, this relationship type should be left blank.
The criteria on which the problem/diagnosis is based.
Clinical stage or grade of a problem/diagnosis. Note: May include formal severity assessments.
A narrative description of the related item.

Descriptor for context- or use-case specific label or workflow-related aspect of the diagnostic process which may not be safe to exchange between systems or use in a shared environment. Examples include: active/inactive; primary/secondary; preliminary/provisional/working/final.
Date the problem was recognised by a healthcare provider.
The date and time this problem/diagnosis was recorded.
Measurement of the body weight of an individual.
Description of the state of dress of the person at the time of weighing.
Clothing which may add significantly to weight, including shoes.
Clothing which will not add to weight significantly.
Wearing only a nappy - can add significant weight.
Comment about the measurement of weight.
Record any issues or factors that may impact on the measurement of body weight eg timing in menstrual cycle, timing of recent bowel motion or noting of amputation.
Height, or body length, is measured from crown of head to sole of foot. Height is measured with the individual in a standing position and body length in a recumbent position.
Any timed measurement of height or body length.
The length of the body from crown of head to sole of foot.
Description of the device used to measure height or body length.
Height is measured standing on both feet with weight distributed evenly, heels together and both buttocks and heels in contact with a vertical back board.
Comment about the measurement of body height/length.
Record any issues or factors that may impact on the measurement of body height/length eg noting of amputation.
Length is measured in a fully extended, recumbent position with the pelvis flat, legs extended and feet flexed.
Recordings related to a single human pregnancy which may include more than one fetus or offspring.
The state of this pregnancy enabling computational decision support.
Details of conception or the beginning of pregnancy.
The date of the last menstrual period if known.
The date of conception if known.
Information about the baby or fetus.
The expected date of birth or delivery (EDD).
The date of birth of this baby or fetus.
The basis for the estimated date of birth.
Basis for estimated date of birth
The means by which the baby was born.
Number of previous pregnancies of more than 20 weeks.
The number of fetuses in this pregnancy at a particular gestation.
True if there have been no prior pregnancies.
The weight of this baby or fetus at birth.
True if the baby was breast fed.
The date the mother stopped breastfeeding this baby.
The age of the baby when breastfeeding ceased (duration).
The estimated age of the baby from LMP at the time of birth.
Number of miscarriages prior to this pregnancy.
The number of terminations of pregnancy prior to this pregnancy.
The number of pregnancies prior to this pregnancy.
The model of care planned for birth.
The model of care at the time of birth.
The number of fetuses at a given gestation.
The gestation at the time of estimation of the number of fetuses.
Details of labour (can be mulitple in unusual circumstances).
The beginning of stage 1 of labour.
Information about the rupture of membranes.
The type of amniotic membrane rupture.
Rupture of the membranes by procedure.
The time of the rupture of the membranes.
Augmentation of labour apart from rupture of membranes.
The date and time of beginning augmentation of labour.
The date and time of onset of the complication.
More detailed information about intervention(s) leading to birth.
Forceps applied to the head low in pelvis.
Forceps applied to the head high in the pelvis.
Forceps applied to the head and rotated prior to traction.
Ventouse applied to the head low in the pelvis.
Unplanned and arising as a result of clinical course.
Planned in advance and undertaken prior to situation arising.
The duration of augmentation of labour.
The time between rupture of the membranes and birth.
Did the intervention lead to birth.
Grouping of neonatal complications, if any.
The name of the fetal or neonatal complications.
Date of onset of neonatal complications.
Clinical description of the neonatal complications.
Description of the liquor during labour and delivery.
Manouvre to assist birth of shoulders.
Breech presentation with legs extended, hips flexed.
Breech presentation with hips and legs flexed.
Fetus lying transverse in the abdomen.
Breech with one or both legs and hips extended.
Fetus lying obliquely in the uterus.
The age of the child at first breast feed.
Age of onset of breast feeding
The duration of the second stage of labour.
Summary of early infant feeding activity, particularly focused on breast and formula feeding.
Narrative description about the overall feeding history for the infant.
Details about a pattern of feeding.
If commenced at birth, which will be recorded as 0 days, weeks or months, then this could be captured or displayed in a system as 'Birth'.
The age of the infant when the selected type of feeding was commenced.
The age of the infant when the selected type of feeding was ceased.
The predominant type of feeding for a period of time.
The total amount of time that the infant was predominantly breastfed.
The age of the infant when commenced on solid foods.
Additional narrative about the feeding activity not captured in other fields.
The age of the infant when weaned.
Infant was solely breast fed, or the proportion of the volume of milk supplied by breast feeding was significantly greater than the volume from bottled formula.
Infant was solely fed on bottled formula, or the proportion of the volume of milk supplied by feeding with bottled formula was significantly greater than by breast feeding.
The volume of milk supplied by breast feeding was similar to that supplied as bottled formula.
Evaluation to indicate that there is, or is not, a significant risk of this subject of care having, now or in the future, a condition.
The likelihood that this person will develop this condition or suffer in this way in the future
The person is not assessed at being at higher risk than the general population
The person may be of somewhat greater risk of developing the condition
The person is considered to be more likely to develop the condition than the general population
The person is considered to be likely to develop the condition

This archetype may be used to record a single valued test, but will often be specialised or templated to represent multiple value or 'panel' tests. This archetype also acts as the parent for specialisations appropriate for more specific laboratory tests, e.g. microbiology, histopathology.
The findings and interpretation of pathology tests performed on patient-related specimens.

A test result may be for a single analyte, or a group of items, including panel tests. Coding with a terminology, potientially a pre-coordinated term including specimen type, is preferred, where possible. May be coded with LOINC or Snomed-CT. Examples include "Glucose", "Urea and Electrolytes", "Swab", “Cortisol (am)” or "Liver Biopsy".
Identification of the pathology test performed, sometimes including specimen type and patient state.
Multiple formats are allowed but they must be semantically equivalent.
Rich text representation of the entire result as issued by the diagnostic service.
Demographic details of the laboratory with responsibility for the pathology test.
Details of the clinician or organisation who will receive a copy of the pathology test result.
This is an initial or interim result: data may be missing or verification not been performed.
The result is complete and verified by the responsible pathologist.
The result has been modified subsequent to being Final, and is complete and verified by the responsible pathologist.
Concise and clinically contextualised narrative interpretation of the pathology test results.
Equivalent to the Placer Order Identifier.
The local ID assigned to the order by the order requester.

Assigning an identifier to a request by the Radiology lnformation System enables tracking progress of the request and enables linking results to requests. It also provides a reference to assist with enquiries and it is usually equivalent to the HL7 Filler Order Identifier.
The local ID assigned to the test order by the order filler, usually by the Laboratory Information System (LIS).

Details about the specimen if all individual test results are derived from the same specimen. If the specimen type is sufficiently specified with a code in the Test result name, then this additional data is not required. If there are multiple specimens, these may be represented per 'Result group'.
The identifier given to the laboratory test result of a pathology investigation.
The publication status of the entire pathology test result.
The result is unavailable because the test was not started or not completed.
The date and/or time that the entire result was issued for the recorded ‘Overall Test result status’.
For example, biochemistry, haematology. Coding with a terminology is desirable, where possible.
The diagnostic service that performs the examination.
Most result values will be numerical measurements, but others may be coded concepts, free text, or multimedia images.
Details of the clinician or organisation requesting the pathology test result.
Usually there is one test request (or "order") for each result, however in some circumstances multiple test requests may be represented using a single Pathology test result archetype.
Details concerning a single pathology test requested.

If a name or code is used, it is provided by run-time re-naming of the Results may be grouped by specimen, or by some other name or code to describe what binds all the results together. 'Result group' element or may be fixed in a specialised archetype or template. Coding with a terminology, potentially a pre-coordinated term including specimen type, is preferred where possible for the name. Should be coded with LOINC or SNOMED CT.

Results include whatever specific data items pathology labs report as part of the clinical service; it is not confined to measurements. The result is identified by run-time re-naming of the 'Result group' element or may be fixed in a specialised archetype or template. Coding with a terminology, potentially a pre-coordinated term including specimen type, is preferred where possible for the name. Should be coded with LOINC or SNOMED CT. Examples include: glucose, haemoglobin, phenotype, titre, or scatterplot image. If the test result is for a single analyte, then both the "Test Result Name" and the "Result" item will specify the same test.
Specific detailed result, including both the value of the result item, and additional information that may be useful for clinical interpretation.
Details about the individual specimen to which these ‘Result group’ test results refer, where testing of multiple specimens is required.
Coding with a terminology is preferred, where possible.
Single word, phrase or brief description representing the narrative in the 'Conclusion'.
Description of clinical information available at the time of interpretation of results, which may include a link to the original clinical information provided in the test request.
Additional narrative about the test not captured in other fields.
May include statements about significant, unexpected or unreliable. values, or information about the source of the value where this may be relevant to the interpretation of the result.
Additional advice on the applicability of the reference range.
Identification of pathology test requested, where the test requested differs from the test actually performed.
Allows a single test result to contain multiple individual results each with their own status.
The status of the result value.
Additional structured details of pathology test methodology followed. For example, structured details about the laboratory method and data interpretation used.
Summary of the vaccination status for an identified infectious disease or agent.
